  "answer": "The forbidden case mischaracterizes the target's mechanism and the nature of the Linear B evidence. The target does not claim a gradual, visible rise of a disloyal underclass that would be recorded in administrative texts; it posits a rapid, synchronized military-social revolution by groups already operating at the margins—mercenaries, raiders, and 'runners'—who were not the scribal class and whose grievances (debt, land pressure) were precisely the obligations the palace recorded. The 'strengthening of the palace system and loyalty to the wanax' observed in final Linear B tablets is fully consistent with a palace elite that, facing external pressures, was intensifying central control, military conscription, and resource extraction in its last years—a reaction to crisis, not evidence of stability. Such texts are administrative snapshots of the palace's own perspective and efforts at consolidation; they would not record the disloyalty of non-scribal, marginal groups that ultimately attacked the centers. The mechanism explains the targeted burning of archives as an act of erasing those very debt and obligation records, meaning the tablets we have are the palace's final, desperate attempts to reassert authority, not a contradiction of the collapse."
